The paper proposes new distance functions for instance-based learning, which is a common technique in machine learning and falls under the category of supervised learning. The paper specifically addresses the issue of handling nominal and continuous attributes, which is a common problem in many real-world applications. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LG (Machine Learning), followed by cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DM (Data Mining). The paper may also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) and neural networks (cs.NE) since these fields often deal with heterogeneous data types.
